questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Freud&amp;rsquo;s Theory of Psychoanalysis:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Psychoanalysis&amp;nbsp;was founded by Sigmund&amp;nbsp;Freud&amp;nbsp;(1856-1939).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The central hypothesis of Freudian psychoanalysis is that &lt;strong&gt;human behaviour is determined largely by unconscious motives.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According to Freud, the unconscious contains repressed and unpleasant memories as these feelings might create pain or conflict, they are buried in the unconscious.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a &lt;strong&gt;cost-effective psychoanalytic therapy in a naturalistic clinical setting.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This theory helps in uncovering the roots of neurosis.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The term &lt;strong&gt;&amp;lsquo;neurosis&amp;rsquo; means a personality or mental disturbance&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;d&lt;/em&gt;ue to any neurological dysfunction. It includes anxiety, post-traumatic stress, compensation neurosis, depression, etc.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The theory &lt;strong&gt;focuses on the unconscious mind&lt;/strong&gt; and states that childhood experiences shape how a person feels and behaves throughout life.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, the above-mentioned points makes it clear that psychoanalysis helps in exploring the unconscious mind in a clinical setting.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Learning&amp;nbsp;is the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;acquisition of new behaviour&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;or the strengthening or weakening of old behaviour as a result of experience. It represents&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;progressive changes in behaviour&lt;/span&gt;. It also involves the acquisition of knowledge, habits, and attitude.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Environmental factors affecting learning:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;social environment&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; describes how a classroom environment affects or encourages interactions between young children, instructors, and family members.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A well-designed social environment fosters positive peer relationships, promotes pleasant interactions between adults and children, and allows adults to assist children in achieving their social objectives.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;55px&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/22/03/60b68a196f056ae9447b3613_16480493793461.png&quot; width=&quot;180px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The condition of the setting where the learning process takes place can also enhance or interfere in the intake of information. If the rooms are not well ventilated, the lighting poor, the space cramped, the environment excessively noisy or surroundings polluted (e.g., due to smoke from a nearby factory), then there will be interference in the children learning, for the body will be more concerned with protecting itself then procuring more knowledge.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus from the above-mentioned points, it is clear that &lt;strong&gt;the social environment is one of the environmental factors affecting learning.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Intrinsic motivation&lt;/strong&gt; refers to the internal drive and enjoyment that comes from engaging in an activity for its own sake, rather than for external rewards or punishments.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Whe&lt;strong&gt;n children find joy in learning&lt;/strong&gt;, they are more likely to be intrinsically motivated to explore, inquire, and seek knowledge.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Teachers can foster intrinsic motivation by creating a positive and engaging learning environment that emphasizes curiosity, exploration, and discovery.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Teachers can cultivate intrinsic motivation in students, leading to a love for learning and a lifelong desire to explore, inquire, and grow.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus, it is concluded that &lt;strong&gt;option 4 is the correct answer.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The interaction between cognition and emotions is bidirectional, meaning that they can mutually influence and shape each other.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Our thoughts and reasoning can modulate our emotional experiences, and our emotions can affect our cognitive processes.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cognition can influence emotions &lt;/strong&gt;by shaping our thoughts, interpretations, and judgements about a situation, which in turn can lead to specific emotional responses.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For example, if we perceive a situation as threatening, our cognition may trigger fear or anxiety. Similarly, our beliefs, expectations, and knowledge can influence how we experience and interpret emotions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;On the other hand, &lt;strong&gt;emotions can also have a significant impact on cognition&lt;/strong&gt;. Strong emotions can capture our attention, affect our concentration and memory, and influence our decision-making processes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For instance, feeling happy and positive can enhance creativity and problem-solving abilities, while feeling sad or stressed can impair cognitive functioning.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This interconnectedness highlights the importance of considering both cognitive and emotional aspects in understanding human behaviour and learning.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, it is clear that&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;cognition&amp;nbsp;and emotions are intertwined and influence each other.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;theory of a&amp;nbsp;child&amp;#39;s&amp;nbsp;moral development&amp;nbsp;is proposed by&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Lawrence&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Kohlberg&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;1958&lt;/span&gt;. he describes the theory on 3&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;different levels and these 3 levels are further classified into 6 stages.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Pre-conventional level ( 0 to 6 years)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Conventional level (7 years to 11 years)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Post conventional level (Above 11 years)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;The conventional Level of Morality&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;a stage of morality in which:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;children make decisions to &lt;strong&gt;please others.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;children try to &lt;strong&gt;maintain interpersonal relations.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;children make efforts on the approval of others.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, we can conclude that&amp;nbsp;a child trying to build&lt;strong&gt; interpersonal skills so he belongs to the second&amp;nbsp;level of Kohlberg&amp;#39;s moral development theory.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following is/are the basic concepts of John B. Watson?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I. Environmentalism&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;II. Study of emotions&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;III. Practical applications&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;J. B. Watson, an American psychologist, has propounded the&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;theory of behaviourism&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; in which he emphasizes that the &lt;strong&gt;environment is the prime factor in shaping the behaviour and actions of a child. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Basic concepts of John B. Watson:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Habit formation&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Environmentalism&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Study of emotions&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Stimulus-response&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Social intervention&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Eugenics movement&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Practical applications&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, we can say that all the above points are basic concepts of John B Watson.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;According to Jean Piaget, which of the following are the part of adaptation?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(i) Assimilation&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(ii) Accommodation&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(iii) Scaffolding&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(iv) Conditioning&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;According to Jean Piaget&amp;#39;s theory of cognitive development, the process of adaptation involves two complementary processes:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Assimilation: &lt;/strong&gt;This is the process of taking in new information and fitting it into and making it part of an existing cognitive schema. For instance, if a child already has a mental category (or schema) for dogs and they encounter a cat for the first time, they might initially assimilate this information and label the cat as a &amp;quot;dog&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Accommodation:&lt;/strong&gt; This is the process of altering one&amp;#39;s existing schemas or ideas as a result of new information or new experiences. Using the previous example, when the child learns more about cats and realizes that cats and dogs are different, they will accommodate this new information by adjusting their schema for dogs and creating a new schema for cats.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus, it is concluded that&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;(i), (ii) is the correct answer.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/hint-text-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Hint&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;Scaffolding and&amp;nbsp;Conditioning, are not part of Piaget&amp;#39;s theory of adaptation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Scaffolding is a concept from Vygotsky&amp;#39;s theory of learning, where an experienced guide helps a learner to accomplish tasks they could not do alone.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Conditioning refers to a type of learning, such as classical or operant conditioning, where behaviors are learned through associations or consequences, and is not part of Piaget&amp;#39;s model.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;School is an agency for formal education that has its own structure and organization. It is governed by rules and regulations prescribed by the state.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A school will become a true second home for the child if&lt;strong&gt; its environment resembles that of the home environment&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Children spend lots of time in school in learning and playing with peers and teachers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In school, teachers should try their best to provide them with such an environment that could make them feel familiar with.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;School&amp;#39;s friendly environment develops the innate potentialities of the child by providing a nourishing and burden-free environment that makes learning fruitful.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, we conclude that a&amp;nbsp;school will become a true second home for the child if&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;its environment resembles that of the home environment.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;social learning theory of gender development &lt;/strong&gt;emphasizes the ways in which external factors, &lt;strong&gt;such as socialization agents, shape children&amp;rsquo;s gender development.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Canadian-American psychologist, Albert Bandura proposed the social learning theory &lt;/strong&gt;which states that social behavior is acquired through observation and imitation of other&amp;rsquo;s behaviors.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;There are four mediational processes that are essential for a new behavior to be learned. These are:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;width:350px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;Attention&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Behavior needs to be attended to from a wide range of stimuli.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;Retention&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The attended behavior form needs to be retained in one&amp;rsquo;s memory.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;Reproduction&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;One needs to have the required skills and abilities to reproduce the behavior.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Motivation&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;It is also explained as &amp;lsquo;vicarious observation&amp;rsquo; by Bandura, which means that a behavior is enacted only if the individual has observed his consequences as rewarding.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Thus, it is concluded that the&amp;nbsp;Social learning theory&amp;nbsp;was based on how children learn by observing and imitating others&amp;#39; behavior.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table border=&quot;4&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;width:350px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;Trial and error learning&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;Thorndike developed his &lt;strong&gt;theory on the basis of his famous experiment of the cat and the puzzle box.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;He placed a hungry cat in a puzzle box&amp;nbsp;that could be opened only by pressing a particular lever.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;Classical conditioning&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The theory of classical conditioning was proposed by Ivan Pavlov.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;According to classical conditioning, we learn by making associations and relationships among various stimuli.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;Operant conditioning&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;Operant conditioning is another approach to the study of associative learning.&lt;/li&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The term coined by B.F. Skinner.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Learning disabilities refer to a range of disorders that affect the brain&amp;#39;s ability to process, store, and retrieve information. These disorders can impact an individual&amp;#39;s ability to read, write, spell, or perform mathematical calculations, and they are not typically related to intelligence. Understanding the nature of learning disabilities is crucial for providing appropriate support and interventions.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Neurological Disorder:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Characteristics of Learning Disabilities: &lt;/strong&gt;Learning disabilities are primarily associated with neurological factors that affect how the brain processes information. These disorders can manifest in various ways, leading to difficulties in acquiring, organizing, and expressing information.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Brain-Based Challenges:&lt;/strong&gt; Neurological disorders, in the context of learning disabilities, indicate that the challenges individuals face are rooted in the way their brains function. This can affect skills such as reading, writing, and mathematical reasoning.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In conclusion, learning disabilities are indeed associated with neurological factors, making Option 1 - &amp;quot;Neurological Disorder&amp;quot; the correct choice.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
